top.value: The rainfall over most of the cropping areas started late with inadequate amounts in many places up to the end of May 2017. This caused late planting of crops and may result in harvesting delays. At the national level, the further deterioration of macroeconomic conditions has forced prices (of food and non-food items) to climb above levels observed last year. Over half of the South Sudanese population needs humanitarian assistance. Conflict has driven massive displacement and is expected to continue to limit household access to natural sources of food, including fish and wild foods. The daily wage rate for casual labour currently purchases under 3 kilograms of cereal in most areas of the country and, as a result, households face extreme difficulty purchasing sufficient food to meet their basic food needs.In terms of peace, governance and access to land, most parts of Lakes state were affected, mildly, by inter-clan clashes especially in the cattle camps by fighting youth. Throughout the country, there were some incidences of looting of relief food from trucks and warehouses with nearly 670 metric tonnes of food lost in July (15 incidences) compared to 7 and 5 June and May respectively.In Rumbek, which neighbours Yirol, 77 metric tonnes of food items in 3 trucks were looted on July 3 in Mayom village.

This project is to support CCFN provide essential services for CAFOD's supported projects in Nigeria. The grant is designed to support CCFN pay for vital utilities, make attainable staff supervision and training to JDPC and CWSI partners. Also, the hosting costs is part of CAFOD's contribution for the provision of office space to Programme Officer based in Abuja. CCFN uses the funds to procure basic utilities that are necessary for the functionality of the office.

The proposed project is a preparedness intervention that aims to contribute to the efforts of improving the preparedness of Goma and Nyiragongo population to future Nyiragongo eruptions. The overall goal is to contribute to the reduction of deaths, injuries and trauma related to volcanic eruption. It will focus on the 4 high risk zone of Goma and some villages of Nyiragongo territory. The emphasis will be put in schools, and public institutions such as market, prison, center of PLWD, Hospitals established in the targeted zones. For mitigating harm and losses, the project will : Support the improvement of the capacity of participating schools and public institutions in the high-risk zone to prepare for and respond to disasters, especially volcanic eruption; and for the Civil protection and humanitarian actors to have an up to date information on vulnerable persons in order to inform their evacuation plans; Conduct the feasibility study of the evacuation sites; and support GVO early warning system. To make this happen, the project intends to facilitate the elaboration and the drills exercises of Disaster Management plans for volcanic eruption; the acquisition of knowledge of existing risk in the environment and the skills for prevention/mitigation/preparedness measures, especially for risk related to volcanic eruption;  including the acquiring chef of Quarters to collect information on vulnerable persons in the household using KOBO. Thus, beneficiaries will be trained, and will get necessaries capacities to develop their plan, test them and to build the culture of Disaster risk reduction in the area.

The Urban programme aim is to contribute to an inclusive city through capacity strengthening and training of local grassroots housing rights' and neighbourhood organisations in So Paulo in order to improve the living conditions of homeless families and families living in precarious and unsecure housing reducing their vulnerability to social and environmental risks. The specific aim of the programme is to consolidate the capacity of partners to support local organisations to defend pro-poor urban policies, participate in spaces of decision-making and carry out community-level training and capacity building on housing and related rights, and to protect housing rights defenders from persecution. This is the 3rd cycle of the Urban Programme in So Paulo. The expected results are (1) Capacity of 150 local organisations to accompany constituents to monitor and participate in urban planning processes, manage security risks related to their work, and protect the space to participate is built (2) Increased advocacy and networking capacity of housing groups to defend pro-poor urban policies (3) Public debate influenced through targeted and strategic communication with new and existing audiences (4) Increased institutional capacity of partners and local organisations.

Agenda 2030 (which includes the Sustainable Development Goals  SDGs) includes transformational shifts for how the international community approaches sustainable development. These include leaving no-one behind, protecting the environment, deepening participation and tackling inequality. These correspond closely with key aspects of Catholic Social Teaching: preferential option for the poor, care for our common home and people as artisans of their own destiny  all emphasised in Laudato Si. It brings together the cry of the poor and the cry of the earth.

ACLO describes itself as a Christian-inspired organisation  that provides services to organised indigenous and rural men and women in the south of Bolivia to strengthen their capacities in the areas of economic production, political organisation, municipal administration and cultural renewal. ACLO trains these rural and indigenous organisations in human rights and supports them to strengthen their leadership capacity so they can effectively participate in decision-making at community and municipal level. The partner also works to involve women in their community organisations and also to educate the general public about the collective rights of marginalised groups and the need for these rights to be respected. ACLO forms part of CAFOD's rural development programme.

Caritas Norway, in cooperation with the Catholic Agency for Overseas Development (CAFOD) and Trocaire in Partnership (CTP) and Catholic Diocese of Rumbek (CDoR), Lakes State, will provide improved food security to 5400 IDPs and vulnerable host community members, with a strong focus on empowerment of women. The project will also support conflict prevention and peace building through dialogue and reconciliation activities aligned with the peace work at national level centred on the support to South Sudan Council of Churches and their peace initiatives. This project will provide one of the very sparse humanitarian interventions in the severely underserved target area.

The project seeks to improve access to water for multiple uses for Tubanju and Nyamusundu rural Primary Schools and surrounding communities in Chimanimani districts of Zimbabwe through solar powered and gravity piped water scheme.  A mini-hydro electricity generator will be installed on the gravity scheme to supply the school with electricity primarily for lighting, computer powering as well as charging the phones. In addition, the project will construct six squathole toilet blocks per school with handwashing facilities to cater for teachers, people living with disability and mensural hygiene. School Health and Nutrition Clubs will be formed at each school primarily to influence good sanitation and hygiene practices and snack hygiene within the school. The larger community will benefit when pupils relate to their parents the on learned health and nutrition aspects.

This project responds to the Zimbabwe Civil unrest in Zimbabwe which was as a result of a fuel price increase of over 150% announced on January 12th. Responding to the immediate increase, the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Union (ZCTU) and several civil society organisations called for a total national shutdown which people took heed of. All services were shut off and in order to control social media interactions which were regarded as the main medium of calling for the shutdown, there was total internet shutdown by the Government of Zimbabwe. While it is a constitutional right to demonstrate in a peaceful way, the demonstrations turned violent with barricades, roadblocks, and looting. In response, police and military moved to break up the demonstrations employing disproportionate physical force, followed by a campaign of house to house searches. As part of the searches, indiscriminate and targeted assaults and arrests have been widely reported. There are many reports of temporary displacement as residents fled or sought to hide. Numbers are likely to significantly exceed documented cases. For example, the Zimbabwe Council of Churches (ZCC) and Catholic Commission of Justice and Peace (CCJP), both with a national reach in the countrys 10 provinces and with direct contact with the affected, confirmed 600 people have been affected by violent assaults (including rape which is presumed to be under reported given anecdotal accounts). Many of those detained were denied access to medical treatment. Medical facilities were overwhelmed in the immediate aftermath and only those with the worst wounds were treated. As a result, many who are in urgent need of medical care, remain without it.
